## Feature Engineering

### Beyond Lags and Rolling Averages

Lag features and rolling means are the "hello world" of time series. Required but insufficient.

**Velocity and acceleration:**
- d(cases)/dt (velocity) and d²(cases)/dt² (acceleration) — epidemic acceleration is a stronger early warning signal than case count level

**Cross-database joins as features:**
- Hospital capacity utilization (SIH demand / CNES beds) as mortality risk predictor
- Notification-to-hospitalization ratio (SINAN / SIH) as surveillance quality proxy
- Professional density (CNES doctors per 10k pop) as outcome moderator

**Spatial features:**
- Epidemic status in neighboring municipalities (adjacency-weighted, distance-weighted)
- Patient flow networks: hub municipalities see different patterns than spoke municipalities
- Spatial autocorrelation (Moran's I) as a feature — clustered outbreaks ≠ isolated ones

**Anomaly-derived features:**
- Deviation from expected seasonal pattern (residuals from decomposition)
- Z-score relative to same-epi-week historical distribution
- Standardized Incidence Ratio (observed/expected)

**Interaction effects (not just main effects):**
- Age × diagnosis × hospital type
- Urbanization × season (dengue dynamics differ urban vs. rural)
- System capacity × demand (outcomes degrade non-linearly when capacity saturates)

**Information signals:**
- Reporting delay patterns: WHEN municipalities report is itself informative
- Data completeness as a feature: missing fields are not random — they correlate with outcomes

### Feature Engineering Acid Test

1. Is this available at prediction time? (no future leakage)
2. Does this encode a **mechanism**, not just a pattern? (mechanisms generalize, patterns overfit)
3. Would a domain expert say **"I never thought of using that"**?

If #3 is "no", keep going.

